Similarly to the previous homework, we’ll use the “MagicTelescope” dataset. The data is generated to simulate registration of high energy gamma particles. The TARGET column has values either:

  • g - gamma (signal) - we’ll denote by 0,
  • h - hadron (background) - we’ll denote by 1.

Task A¶

A1¶

To make it more interesting, however, this time we'll use CatBoost classifier. CatBoost is a gradient boosting library that uses decision trees. It is similar to XGBoost, but it has some additional features, such as categorical features support. It also has a nice API for hyperparameter tuning, which we'll use in this task.

Due to high computational cost of hyperparameter tuning, we'll use a subset of hyperparameter set I found at Stack Overflow.

The hyperparameters are:

  • depth - depth of the decision trees,
  • iterations - number of learning iterations.

The found hyperparameters are:

Out[23]:
{'depth': 6, 'iterations': 1000}

The best model has a good accuracy on the training set:

Out[24]:
0.930205047318612

And on the test set:

Out[25]:
0.8916929547844374

The fact that it's slightly lower than the accuracy on the training set suggests that the model is a bit overfitted. However, the difference is small, so it shouldn't be a problem.

A6¶

In task A3, when comparing explanations between dalex and shap, while the order of importance of features is similar, the values of SHAP values are different. This is because dalex uses a different method to calculate SHAP values than shap.

Here, SHAP uses a TreeExplainer which is a model-specific and more accurate method, while dalex uses a model-agnostic KernelExplainer. The latter is more computationally expensive and less accurate, but it's also more general and can be used for any model.

Using 1000 background data samples could cause slower run times. Consider using shap.sample(data, K) or shap.kmeans(data, K) to summarize the background as K samples.

  0%|          | 0/100 [00:00<?, ?it/s]
Stored 'mlp_shap_values100' (Explanation)

The KernelExplainer outputs a SHAP value for both classes. To compare it with the CatBoost explainer, we'll take the SHAP value for the positive outcome (h).

We want to find an observation for which SHAP values between the models vary widely. We'll first normalize each of the SHAP values vector by dividing it by its Euclidean norm. That's because the scale of SHAP values depends on the scale of output of each model.

Then we'll find the observation for which the difference between the normalized SHAP values is the largest.
